rComments:
uOttawa better be paying this man. He's a treasure. Not easy, but fair. His lectures are top-tier. Looked forward to every class. My advice: do the readings and make your own briefs, then supplement them with the in-class material. 

PS. Read exams carefully. The devil is in the details.

He is the worst prof I have ever had. He is rude, condescending, inappropriate and demeaning. He doesn't respect class time and thinks he is better than everyone. He acts like he knows better than all the courts. He needs a wake up call on respect. On exams, he will frequently give out 0s on questions even though you got most of the elements.
Good prof who may be perceived improperly by people. He cares but is extremely busy but is honest, direct and wants you to be better.

Professor Daimsis is an amazing professor. He knows his stuff. He's tough, critical and doesn't pull punches. Not because he's mean-spirited but because he cares and wants you to improve. That became really obvious when I mooted with him. It's any student's honour to be coached and mentored by him if you can handle it.

Brilliant prof who knows his stuff and genuinely cares about students' success. His lecturing style is super clear and compelling; he's a great speaker and has no trouble holding the class's attention. The subject matter (international arbitration) was really interesting, especially taught from his expert perspective. Highly recommend.
Best teacher I've had in my whole law school career!

He is one of the best professors at UoO, at least that I've had. His lectures are extremely engaging, you barely have to take down any notes because he conveys the material so well and in such a manner that just makes sense. Hilarious too. Overall, excellent. I would not hesitate to take him again. You will learn tons in this class.

Prof Daimsis is by far the best professor. He believes in his students' competence and refuses to spoon-feed case ratios. His exams are extremely fair! Yes, he has high expectations during lectures for students to come prepared and understand the cases, but his exams are solely based on information discussed, and aren't filled with trick-questions

A prof unafraid to poke fun at the ever-so-slightly non-PC material. What a breath of fresh air. Course is engaging and he encourages participation. Muster up the courage to ask/answer questions in class, and I guarantee you'll walk away with solid understanding of contracts. Really knows his stuff, and will actually help if you ask in office hrs.

Good prof. Laid back and funny. Mandatory 1L class (content/PPTs set by the school?), so the material wasn't the most exciting, but he does a great job sifting through the important/not-so-important info. Teases students but isn't mean... ADR will be fun if you keep this in mind & participate.

He's been described as a "moot god" at school before, hence "respected" in my tags. He's funny, he gets through the material, and does indeed give off that "sleezy lawyer" vibe. That said, he cares about teaching students how to be lawyers rather than simply teaching student the law. If you can get him for ADR, I recommend him.

Great guy but not a great prof, hes lectures are a tad boring and detailed but then again there are very few classes he shows up for. The class itself is interactive with lots of opportunities for engaging questions and debate. Lively class overall and generally nice guy who also happens to be the moot coach for the law school.

Big fish in a little pond syndrome. Brags a lot to elicit the admiration of students. Arrogant demeanor. Phones it in during most lectures (probably bc he's bored with material he knows well, and it's all about him, not about your learning). Superficial charm - has that sleazy lawyer vibe. But you will learn some useful techniques.

This class is challenging but rewarding. This class will prepare you for the "real world" and is a must-take if you are prepared to put the work into it. I was also better prepared for my contracts exam because he compares and contrasts  international contracts with the common law. He will make you think outside of the box.

Listen 0Ls, if you take his thematic class be ready for an intense wrap up to the course in terms of workload (for a 1L thematic course anyway), but Daimsis is hands-down the best prof I had this year. If you're interested in the subject, you won't regret it.
You probably wont get an A, but you have to be really dumb and not pay attention at all to get lower than a B.  Just listen to what he says in class and do his practice exams and youll do fine.

Daimsis is an excellent professor.  Those complaining about him are just poor law students who do not know how to write an exam. He expects clarity in writing and well thought out answers. If you're a crappy writer and do not understand legal precedents, his class is not for you. One of the best uOttawa has. Heads up the Moots for a REASON.

If you’re an extremely gifted student this professor is for you however, if you are not stay as far away as you possibly can from this showboat. Oh he’ll entertain you BUT WITH his final I guarantee that any laughter will come to a screeching halt when you see what he serves up to you. Use to A's & B's, welcome to your 1st C or worse!

Great prof, funny, knows is his stuff about international trade law and UNCITRAL.  One of the most engaging classes I've had at law school.  U of o is lucky to have this prof... let's hope the school doesn't screw up and lose him to the private sector.

Not as impressed as some other posters. I wasn't taken by his superficial charm and found that he was incredibly condescending; he quickly skimmed over cases including some very tricky concepts. Contrary to what he says, he does try to trick you in his NP contracts exam which is 2 hours but should be 3. Doesn't always respond to emails....
Prof with benefits ;)

Hard maker no doubt but fair.  If you show interest and demonstrate that you are trying he will help you to achieve the success you're working towards.  Was awarded capital educator's award for 2011 and by no accident.  I entered contracts law dreading it and walked out loving contracts.  Must take class.  He will teach you the law correctly.
Amazing prof! Very enthusiastic and passionate. Makes you work hard and think for yourself. Can be arrogant and sarcastic, but is still overall entertaining and makes you want to succeed!

Should not be teaching first year contracts. Displayed palpable disregard for the students in his class. Does not hold regular office hours. Canceled classes. Skipped over readings. Did not review course material prior to exams. Marking was arbitrary. Avoid.

Good first year contracts prof, will force you to think mroe like a lawyer and work things out on your own. He is friendly, but some find him intimidating. However, he slacks off in 2nd term to focus on his moot teams. He is a fair marker (although consistency is questionable) but he will try to trip you up on the exam, and then deny it.

Great guy to have as a first year prof. Teaches the law and gives you the tools you need to think for yourself - but he doesn't make it easy. You have to work for it, which in the long run is a good thing. Also, if you say stupid things in class he will call you out on it, so think before you talk.
he is an amasing prof
Doesn't return emails.
No Comments

had him in 2007-2008 for 1st year contracts - very simple lectures, not much controversy/theory/critical thinking at all. he wants you to know the facts very practically. efficency, not creativity, is the name of the game on the exam. outside of class, he offers more depth than you'll get from the somewhat superficial lectuers. points for clarity.

Really nice guy. Funny, sarcastic and really knows his contracts and business law. Cares about students doing well but getting there fairly. Not your typical prof and will make you think about the bigger world view. Don't take him if you are not prepared to think as you're writing your exam. Read questions and facts carefully!!!
